Here is an example of buying a diagonal spread vs. buying a naked call:

-On the left you\xe2\x80\x99ve spent $26.10 ($2#610) for one 11/27 $470 call 
    -break even is $496.05 on 11/27 
    -time decay (theta) is -2.85 or $285 a day; so every day it loses about $285 in value

-On the right you\xe2\x80\x99ve spent $26.60 ($2#660) on a 12/11 $480 call (long) and 11/27 $500 call (short) 
      -break even is between $480.69 - $548.83 on 11/27 
       -theta is the same at -2.85
       -if TSLA closes below $511 on 11/27 you call roll the short call to a 12/4 call and collect MORE premium on the short call as you still own the 12/4 call

Obviously the naked call offers more upside. But the spread offers a realistic chance of turning a profit and feels a lot less like gambling.
